Negative Interest Club
Brussels—In most of the past decade, central banks have made limited progress in curbing the powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero, and through large-scale bond purchases has implemented unprecedented asset expansion on multiple occasions.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have all followed the Federal Reserve, implementing their own versions of the so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not been reasonably improved anywhere.
Despite these countries all being in a struggle against deflationary pressures, their monetary policy — as well as their economic performance — are diverging.
Now that the US and the UK have a strong enough growth rate, they can exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are going further with QE, pushing long-term policy rates further into the negative zone.
Why this difference?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had a current account deficit, making them debtors, while the eurozone and Japan have had a current account surplus, making them creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtors but harm creditors, so the introduction of negative interest rates after the global economic crisis stimulated the recovery of the United States and the United Kingdom, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor countries in the world -- countries with large and persistent current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland -- have negative interest rates, not only long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also medium-term bonds.
This is certainly not a good thing.
Although low-interest rates have little effect, these central banks still stick to this policy.
If you say that QE or reducing interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will dodge and say that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — — from the surface, this is unassailable.
But actually, this has many loopholes.
Even basic economics courses mention the unique phenomenon of the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in a certain environment, reducing interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because the decrease in interest rates reduces the income of savers, they will reduce their spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
All of these are not denying the general rule — — they constitute the foundation of modern monetary decision-making — — reducing interest rates can stimulate consumption and other expenditures.
Only the effect is different due to the different debt status of the economy.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what the creditor loses due to the extremely low interest rate, the debtor should benefit.
However, in an economy with a large amount of net foreign asset positions, creditors are naturally more than debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effect of the interest rate floor monetary policy is different in creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not particularly important because foreign asset positions are often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, major industrialized economies have large and increasingly diverse foreign asset positions partly due to leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
Indeed, leverage continues to rise at the national level.
Although the trade surplus has overall eased since the financial crisis began, it has not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to consolidate their creditor status, and diverge from deficit economies.
Some major commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, and thus became the main exception to the differentiation of foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, the world oil price has plummeted, and the wealth trend of these countries has reversed.
Their export revenues have sharply decreased — — many countries have halved — — forcing them to run a deficit and rely on the massive sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodity boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending is inevitable.
Industrialized economies face a completely different challenge.
Their problems — — from a certain point of view, is a luxury problem — — is to ensure consumers spend the unexpected wealth gained from the decline in import prices.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to have advanced this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole, the eurozone is a creditor economy, it also has debtor countries.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have frequent trade surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But the current account surplus in traditional debtor countries is too high, leading to an increasingly asymmetric debtor-creditor situation.
The most noteworthy thing is that since the financial crisis broke out, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, which means that the surplus accumulated by Germany in this period has exceeded its historical total.
According to the current trend, Germany's creditor position may increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
The central bank governor should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem not to be patient, and their heads are aching from low inflation, although the output gap is being filled slowly, and the United States and Japan have achieved full employment.
Central bank governors of debt countries must stop using more monetary easing that may be unfavorable to production to manipulate the economy.
On the other hand, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
European Central Bank Governor Draghi recently admitted that the current monetary policy stance may not be effective in today's global environment.
However, committing to more of the old ways is not the solution.
